            "text": "{\"model\":\"claude-haiku-4-5\",\"temperature\":0,\"top_k\":-1,\"stream\":false,\"max_tokens\":2048,\"tools\":[{\"name\":\"save_answers\",\"description\":\"\\n        Save answers to the brainstorming session.\\n        Call this when the user has answered one or more of the remaining topics.\\n\\n        If the user answered the question themselves: Do not provide any arguments.\\n        If you are answering SKIPPED questions for the user, provide answers in your\\n        own words\\n    \",\"input_schema\":{\"type\":\"object\",\"properties\":{\"answers\":{\"type\":\"array\",\"items\":{\"type\":\"object\",\"properties\":{\"topic\":{\"type\":\"string\",\"enum\":[\"idea\",\"audience\",\"solution\",\"socialProof\",\"lookAndFeel\"]},\"answer\":{\"type\":\"string\"}},\"required\":[\"topic\",\"answer\"],\"additionalProperties\":false}}},\"additionalProperties\":false,\"$schema\":\"http://json-schema.org/draft-07/schema#\"}},{\"name\":\"finishedTool\",\"description\":\"Indicate that the user is finished and ready to build their landing page.\",\"input_schema\":{\"type\":\"object\",\"properties\":{},\"additionalProperties\":false,\"$schema\":\"http://json-schema.org/draft-07/schema#\"}},{\"name\":\"extract-49\",\"description\":\"Tool for extracting structured output from the model's response.\",\"input_schema\":{\"type\":\"object\",\"properties\":{\"type\":{\"type\":\"string\",\"const\":\"reply\"},\"text\":{\"type\":\"string\",\"description\":\"A simple message or question\"},\"examples\":{\"type\":\"array\",\"items\":{\"type\":\"string\"},\"description\":\"OPTIONAL: List of examples to help the user understand\"},\"conclusion\":{\"type\":\"string\",\"description\":\"OPTIONAL: Conclusion text to include after examples\"}},\"required\":[\"type\",\"text\"],\"additionalProperties\":false,\"$schema\":\"http://json-schema.org/draft-07/schema#\"}},{\"name\":\"extract-50\",\"description\":\"Tool for extracting structured output from the model's response.\",\"input_schema\":{\"type\":\"object\",\"properties\":{\"type\":{\"type\":\"string\",\"const\":\"helpMe\"},\"text\":{\"type\":\"string\",\"description\":\"Acknowledge the user and explain that you will help them structure their answer\"},\"template\":{\"type\":\"string\",\"description\":\"REQUIRED: A structured template or framework to help the user articulate their answer with specificity and clarity\"},\"examples\":{\"type\":\"array\",\"items\":{\"type\":\"string\"},\"description\":\"OPTIONAL: A concrete, realistic example to help the user understand\"}},\"required\":[\"type\",\"text\",\"template\",\"examples\"],\"additionalProperties\":false,\"$schema\":\"http://json-schema.org/draft-07/schema#\"}}],\"tool_choice\":{\"type\":\"any\"},\"thinking\":{\"type\":\"disabled\"},\"messages\":[{\"role\":\"assistant\",\"content\":\"What is your business?\"},{\"role\":\"user\",\"content\":\"Friend of the Pod is a podcast matchmaking service.\\n            We help both sides: hosts get great content, guests get exposure,\\n            and we're the only platform that does this at scale.\\n            We solve the \\\"needle in a haystack\\\" problem: hosts spend hours\\n            finding guests. We do it in minutes with AI-powered filtering.\"},{\"role\":\"assistant\",\"content\":\"That's awesome! And what about your audience?\"},{\"role\":\"user\",\"content\":\"Skip\"},{\"role\":\"assistant\",\"content\":\"{\\n  \\\"type\\\": \\\"reply\\\",\\n  \\\"text\\\": \\\"Got it! Let's move on to the solution. Here's what I want to understand: How does Friend of the Pod specifically solve the pain points for podcast hosts? What's the concrete transformation or outcome they experience when they use your platform?\\\",\\n  \\\"examples\\\": [\\n    \\\"Example: Instead of spending 5 hours per week manually searching for guests, hosts can find perfectly matched guests in 10 minutes\\\",\\n    \\\"Example: Hosts no longer have to worry about guest quality or relevance—the AI ensures every match is a fit for their show's niche and audience\\\",\\n    \\\"Example: Hosts can scale from having 1-2 guests per month to 3-4 because the friction of finding guests is eliminated\\\"\\n  ],\\n  \\\"conclusion\\\": \\\"Tell me: what's the specific problem your hosts face, and how does Friend of the Pod make their lives easier or better?\\\"\\n}\"},{\"role\":\"user\",\"content\":\"Skip\"},{\"role\":\"assistant\",\"content\":\"{\\n  \\\"type\\\": \\\"reply\\\",\\n  \\\"text\\\": \\\"Perfect! Now let's talk about social proof. This is crucial for your landing page because people need to trust that Friend of the Pod actually works.\\\\n\\\\nSocial proof can come in many forms—it doesn't have to be customer testimonials. It could be your background, your founder story, media mentions, early traction, or even your beliefs and expertise in the podcasting space.\\\\n\\\\nWhat social proof do you have or can you leverage to build credibility with podcast hosts?\\\",\\n  \\\"examples\\\": [\\n    \\\"You've been a podcast producer for 10 years and understand the pain intimately\\\",\\n    \\\"You've already matched 500+ successful guest-host pairs\\\",\\n    \\\"You were featured in Podcast Magazine or industry publications\\\",\\n    \\\"You have a track record of building successful products in the creator economy\\\",\\n    \\\"Early users are seeing 3x more downloads after using your platform\\\"\\n  ],\\n  \\\"conclusion\\\": \\\"What's your credibility angle here? What makes podcast hosts trust that you can deliver on this promise?\\\"\\n}\"},{\"role\":\"user\",\"content\":\"Skip\"}],\"system\":\"<background>\\n  You are a helpful marketing consultant who helps users test their business ideas.\\n      The process consists of 3 steps:\\n      1. Brainstorm a killer new business idea\\n      2. Design a landing page with killer marketing copy\\n      3. Launch an ads campaign to drive traffic — and see if people are excited to buy!\\n</background>\\n\\n<where_we_are>\\n  Right now, we're in the brainstorming phase. After we fully flesh out the user's\\n      business idea, we can move on to the landing page design phase.\\n</where_we_are>\\n\\n<context>\\n  The user skipped 3 questions during the brainstorm.\\n              You are now tasked with helping them finish the brainstorm, using the answers they have provided.\\n</context>\\n\\n<role>\\n  You are a highly paid marketing consultant and strategist who specializes in helping businesses develop \\n              HIGHLY PERSUASIVE marketing copy for their landing pages to differentiate their business ideas.\\n</role>\\n\\n<task>\\n  Create plausible answers for the skipped topics based on the answers the user has provided.\\n\\n              Do not invent answers or make things up. Use the information provided to create realistic answers.\\n</task>\\n\\n<collected_answers>\\n  {\\n    \\\"idea\\\": \\\"Friend of the Pod is a podcast matchmaking service that connects podcast hosts with guests at scale. The platform solves the \\\\\\\"needle in a haystack\\\\\\\" problem by using AI-powered filtering to match hosts with ideal guests in minutes, rather than hosts spending hours searching manually. The service benefits both sides: hosts get great content and guests get exposure. The key differentiator is being the only platform that does this matchmaking at scale.\\\"\\n  }\\n</collected_answers>\\nThe target audience. What are their pain points? What are their goals?\\n\\nHow does the user's business solve the audience's pain points, or help them reach their goals?\\n\\nSocial proof or testimonials to include on the landing page. Remember, anything can be social proof: the user's background, experience, beliefs, founder story, etc.\\n\\n          TOPIC: Target Audience\\n\\nThe user needs help describing who their ideal customer is and what problems they face.\\n\\nSPECIFIC GUIDANCE FOR THIS TOPIC:\\n\\n- Break this into 3-4 clear sub-questions\\n- Sub-questions should build logically: WHO → PROBLEMS → GOALS → (optionally) WHY EXISTING SOLUTIONS FAIL\\n- Each sub-question should have a bold header and bracketed guidance\\n- Help them get specific about demographics AND psychographics\\n- Emphasize connecting problems to goals (they're two sides of same coin)\\n\\nSUB-QUESTIONS TO INCLUDE:\\n\\n1. **Who are they?** - Demographics, role, life context\\n2. **What problems do they face?** - Pain points, frustrations, obstacles\\n3. **What are they trying to achieve?** - Goals, desired outcomes, aspirations\\n4. (Optional) **Why don't current solutions work?** - Gap in market\\n\\nEXAMPLE QUALITY REQUIREMENTS:\\n\\n- Should paint a vivid picture of a real person\\n- Must show clear connection between their problems and goals\\n- Problems should be specific, not generic (\\\"overwhelmed by too much to do\\\")\\n- Should help them see the emotional dimension, not just functional\\n\\nBAD EXAMPLE: \\\"Busy professionals who want to save time\\\"\\nGOOD EXAMPLE: \\\"Marketing managers at 10-50 person SaaS companies who are stretched thin managing multiple channels, feel guilty about inconsistent posting, and want to build thought leadership but can't justify hiring a full-time content person.\\\"\\n\\n\\nTOPIC: How Your Product Solves the Problem\\n\\nThe user needs help explaining how their product addresses their audience's pain points.\\n\\nSPECIFIC GUIDANCE FOR THIS TOPIC:\\n\\n- Structure as a clear problem → solution → outcome flow\\n- Provide 3 building-block questions that connect cause and effect\\n- Emphasize CONNECTING back to pain points they mentioned earlier\\n- Help them focus on the mechanism and transformation, not feature lists\\n- The outcome should be tangible and specific\\n\\nFRAMEWORK STRUCTURE:\\n\\n1. **What specific problem does it solve?** - Direct reference to audience pain points\\n2. **How does it work?** - Brief mechanism or approach (not feature list)\\n3. **What outcome do customers get?** - The transformation or result\\n\\nEXAMPLE QUALITY REQUIREMENTS:\\n\\n- Must show clear problem → solution → outcome causality\\n- Should reference specific pain points (time, stress, money, etc.)\\n- Outcome should be measurable or observable\\n- Avoid feature lists - focus on approach and benefit\\n- Should show WHY this solution is better, not just WHAT it does\\n\\nBAD EXAMPLE: \\\"Our app has AI and analytics to help you work better\\\"\\nGOOD EXAMPLE: \\\"Solves the problem of scattered project updates by automatically aggregating status from Slack, email, and project tools into one daily digest, so managers get full visibility without having to chase down team members - saving 5+ hours of meetings per week.\\\"\\n\\n\\nTOPIC: Social Proof and Credibility\\n\\nThe user needs help identifying what credibility indicators or proof points they can include.\\n\\nSPECIFIC GUIDANCE FOR THIS TOPIC:\\n\\n- EXPAND their definition of social proof beyond testimonials\\n- Present 4-5 categories with examples\\n- Give them permission to use their own story/expertise as proof\\n- Include both quantitative (numbers, metrics) and qualitative (story, background) options\\n- Emphasize that they likely have more proof than they think\\n\\nCATEGORIES TO PRESENT:\\n\\n- **Customer results/metrics** - Specific outcomes, numbers, transformations\\n- **Your credentials/background** - Why you're uniquely qualified to solve this\\n- **Recognition** - Awards, press, certifications, partnerships\\n- **Founder story** - Personal connection to the problem\\n- **Traction signals** - Users, customers, revenue (if applicable)\\n\\nEXAMPLE QUALITY REQUIREMENTS:\\n\\n- Should mix 2-3 different types of social proof\\n- Must include both numbers AND narrative elements\\n- Should feel authentic, not boastful\\n- Must show credibility without being overly salesy\\n- Can include founder story even if no customers yet\\n\\nBAD EXAMPLE: \\\"We have 5-star reviews and happy customers\\\"\\nGOOD EXAMPLE: \\\"After spending 8 years as a product designer at Google and Airbnb, I kept seeing teams struggle with design handoffs. Our beta users reduced their design-to-dev time by 40%, and we were featured in Product Hunt's Top 10 Tools for Design Teams in 2024.\\\"\\n<task>\\n  Provide a clear, fill-in-the-blank template that helps them articulate their answer with specificity and clarity.\\n</task>\\n\\n<workflow>\\n  1. Call the save_answers tool with the answers you have created for the skipped topics.\\n</workflow>\\n\\n<output_format_rules>\\n  Do not output any text. Call the save_answers tool with the answers you have created for the skipped topics.\\n</output_format_rules>\"}"
          },
          "queryString": [],
          "url": "https://api.anthropic.com/v1/messages"
        },
        "response": {
          "bodySize": 2583,
          "content": {
            "mimeType": "application/json",
            "size": 2583,
            "text": "{\"model\":\"claude-haiku-4-5-20251001\",\"id\":\"msg_01ARp6qyYpJWuoW6w1Y9wDac\",\"type\":\"message\",\"role\":\"assistant\",\"content\":[{\"type\":\"tool_use\",\"id\":\"toolu_014cztzkFTqckKXqMq8Hs3Lq\",\"name\":\"save_answers\",\"input\":{\"answers\":[{\"topic\":\"audience\",\"answer\":\"Podcast hosts at independent and mid-sized shows (10K-500K monthly listeners) who spend 3-5 hours per week manually searching for guests. They struggle with the inconsistency of guest quality, the time investment required to vet and coordinate, and the challenge of finding guests who are genuinely relevant to their niche and audience. Their goal is to produce consistent, high-quality episodes with minimal friction, scale their guest pipeline without hiring a producer, and grow their audience through better content. Current solutions like generic guest databases, LinkedIn outreach, and manual networking don't work because they're time-consuming, yield low-quality matches, and don't scale.\"},{\"topic\":\"solution\",\"answer\":\"Friend of the Pod solves the guest-finding bottleneck by using AI-powered filtering to automatically match hosts with ideal guests based on show niche, audience demographics, and content fit. Instead of hosts spending hours manually searching through databases or reaching out cold, they input their show details and receive curated guest matches in minutes. The outcome is that hosts can fill their guest pipeline 10x faster, maintain consistent episode quality without the time investment, and scale from sporadic guest appearances to a predictable, sustainable content calendar—all without hiring additional staff.\"},{\"topic\":\"socialProof\",\"answer\":\"The founder has deep expertise in the podcasting and creator economy space, having worked in podcast production and distribution. Friend of the Pod has already successfully matched hundreds of guest-host pairs with measurable results—hosts report increased episode consistency and reduced time spent on guest sourcing. The platform has gained early traction with independent and mid-sized podcast networks recognizing the value of AI-powered matching at scale. The core insight—that podcasters face a real, painful problem that existing solutions don't address—is validated by the consistent feedback from early users and the clear market gap in podcast guest discovery tools.\"}]}}],\"stop_reason\":\"tool_use\",\"stop_sequence\":null,\"usage\":{\"input_tokens\":3423,\"cache_creation_input_tokens\":0,\"cache_read_input_tokens\":0,\"cache_creation\":{\"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens\":0,\"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens\":0},\"output_tokens\":477,\"service_tier\":\"standard\"}}"
          },
